    <definition xml:id="def-proposition">
      <p>
        A <term>mathematical statement</term> (also called a <term>proposition</term>) is a sentence
        which is either true or false.
      </p>
    </definition>

    <p>
      Each of the following is a mathematical statement. Depending on the matrices
      or vectors involved, each may be true or false.
    </p>

    <ul marker="">
      <li>(1) &#160; <m>A\vec x = \vec b</m> is consistent.</li>
      <li>(2) &#160; <m>[A \; | \; \vec b]</m> is row equivalent to <m>[C \; | \; \vec d]</m>.</li>
      <li>(3) &#160; <m>A\vec x = \vec 0</m> has a non‑trivial solution.</li>
      <li>(4) &#160; The columns of <m>A</m> are linearly dependent.</li>
      <li>(5) &#160; <m>T(\vec x)=A\vec x</m> is onto.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      For example, (1) is true if
      <m>A=\begin{bmatrix} 1\amp 0\\ 0\amp 1\\ 0\amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m> and
      <m>\vec b=\begin{bmatrix} 1\\ 2\\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>,
      but false if <m>A=\begin{bmatrix} 1\amp 0\\ 0\amp 1\\ 0\amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m> and
      <m>\vec b=\begin{bmatrix} 1\\ 2\\ 3 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
    </p>

    <problem xml:id="ex2-q1" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Pick <em>one</em> of the statements (2)–(5) above.
          Give:
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>a choice of vectors/matrices that makes the statement true,</li>
          <li>a choice that makes the same statement false.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>
          Verify your answers using appropriate calculations.
        </p>
        <p>
          <em>Note:</em> Please write the problem statement you are solving to help the grader.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <p><vspace amount="2.5in"/></p>
    </problem>
