  <page>
    <title>Combining Statements</title>

    <p>
      Statements can be combined using logical connectives such as
      <em>and</em>, <em>or</em>, and <em>implies</em>.
    </p>

    <ul marker="">
      <li>(6) &#160; <m>[A \; | \; \vec b]</m> is row equivalent to <m>[C \; | \; \vec d]</m>
        <strong>and</strong> <m>A\vec x=\vec b</m> is consistent.
      </li>
      <li>(7) &#160;  <m>A\vec x=\vec 0</m> has a non‑trivial solution
        <strong>or</strong> <m>T(\vec x)=A\vec x</m> is onto.
      </li>
      <li>(8a) &#160; The columns of <m>A</m> are linearly dependent
        <strong>implies</strong> <m>A\vec x=\vec 0</m> has a non‑trivial solution.
      </li>
      <li>(8a) &#160; If the columns of <m>A</m> are linearly dependent,
        <strong>then</strong> <m>A\vec x=\vec 0</m> has a non‑trivial solution.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Implications are commonly written using <strong>if–then</strong> language.
      The statements (8a) and (8b) express the same idea using different wording.
    </p>

    <p>
      An implication is <em>true</em> when the truth of the “if” part
      forces the “then” part to be true.
    </p>

    <p>
      For example, if the columns of <m>A</m> are linearly dependent,
      then there is a free variable in <m>A\vec x=\vec 0</m>,
      yielding a non‑trivial solution. Thus, (8a) and (8b) are true.
    </p>

    <p>
      An implication is <em>false</em> if there exists a counterexample where
      the “if” part is true but the “then” part is false.
    </p>


    <ul marker="">
          <li>(9) &#160; If <m>A\vec x=\vec b</m> and <m>A\vec y=\vec b</m>,
          then <m>A(\vec x+\vec y)=\vec b</m>.</li>
    </ul>

      <p>
        This implication is false. For example, let
        <m>A=\begin{bmatrix} 1\amp 1\\ 1\amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</m> and
        <m>\vec b=\begin{bmatrix} 3\\ 3 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
        Then <m>\vec x=\begin{bmatrix} 1\\ 2 \end{bmatrix}</m> and
        <m>\vec y=\begin{bmatrix} 3\\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m> both satisfy
        <m>A\vec x=\vec b</m>, but
        <m>A(\vec x+\vec y)=\begin{bmatrix} 6\\ 6 \end{bmatrix}\neq\vec b</m>.
      </p>
 
