  <!-- ================= PAGE 7 ================= -->
  <page>
    <title>Quantifiers</title>

    <p>
      Some statements involve <em>quantifiers</em>.
      The two most common are:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>for all</strong> (universal quantifier),</li>
      <li><strong>for some</strong> (existential quantifier).</li>
    </ul>

    <p> Notice the quantifiers in the follow statements.</p>

    <ul marker="">
      <li>
        (10) &#160; If <m>A\vec x=\vec b</m> is consistent <em>for some</em>
        <m>\vec b\in\mathbb{R}^m</m>, then <m>A</m> has a pivot in every row.
      </li>
      <li>
        (11) &#160; If <m>A</m> does not have a pivot in every column and
        <m>T(\vec x)=A\vec x</m>, then <em>for every</em>
        <m>\vec x_1\neq\vec x_2</m> we have
        <m>T(\vec x_1)=T(\vec x_2)</m>.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <title>Question Q3</title>

    <problem xml:id="ex2-q3" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>
          For statements (10) and (11):
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>Identify the propositions.</li>
          <li>Both statements are false. Provide a counterexample for <em>one</em> of them and explain why the counterexample works.</li>
        </ol>

      <p>
          <em>Hint:</em> For (10), choose <m>A</m> and <m>\vec b</m> such that
          <m>A\vec x=\vec b</m> is consistent but <m>A</m> lacks a pivot in every row.
      </p>

        <p>
          <em>Hint:</em> For (11), choose <m>A</m> without a pivot in every column and
          vectors <m>\vec x_1\neq\vec x_2</m> such that
          <m>T(\vec x_1)\neq T(\vec x_2)</m>.
        </p>
        </statement>
      </problem>
